    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Considering the history of pelvic and tibial fractures, clinical presentation with acute confusion and shortness of breath on day 2, and chest X-ray findings of bilateral lung infiltrates, fat embolism is the most likely diagnosis. Fat embolism is a common problem following trauma to or surgery of lower extremities. These conditions result in fat escaping from bone marrow into circulation and forming emboli. Symptoms of fat embolism syndrome typically present 24 to 72 hours after the insult and involve lungs, brain, and skin, resulting in a triad of respiratory, neurological, and cutaneous manifestations. Lung problems including rapid breathing, shortness of breath (dyspnea), and hypoxemia are the earliest findings in fat embolism and virtually exist in all patients. Neurological problems often follow respiratory involvement and include irritability, agitation, headache, confusion, seizures, or coma. Petechial skin rash is caused by occlusion of small blood vessels with emboli, most commonly on the upper torso and axillary area, and is seen in approximately 60% of patients. Diagnosis is made based on history and physical exam findings, as well as exclusion of other possible causes. Investigations include chest X-rays, blood tests, and CT scan. Option A (pulmonary embolism) is less likely given the history and presentation. Option C (air embolism) typically causes more acute, severe hemodynamic collapse. Option D (pneumonia) would typically present after 48 hours with fever, cough, and sputum. Option E (drug withdrawal) is inconsistent with the clinical picture.`,
