    id: "em-amedex-0004",
    topic: "Emergency Medicine",
    subtopic: "Carbon Monoxide Poisoning Management",
    stem: `A 32-year-old man is brought to the emergency department of a local hospital after he was recovered from a fire in a building. He was working in his office in that building when the fire started and was barricaded in the room for approximately 20 minutes before firemen were able to break into the room surrounded by fire and full of smoke. Which one of the following is the correct method of giving him oxygen?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `2L/min via nasal cannula.` },
      { label: "B", text: `6L/min via Venturi mask.` },
      { label: "C", text: `5-10L/min via simple face mask.` },
      { label: "D", text: `10-15L/min via non-rebreathing mask.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Transferring him to hyperbaric oxygen chamber.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `In every victim of a fire, especially in closed spaces, carbon monoxide poisoning should always be considered a possibility to investigate and treat immediately. Carbon monoxide (CO) is an extremely poisonous, odourless, tasteless, and colourless gas produced when there is incomplete combustion of carbon-containing fuels (e.g., coal, petroleum, peat, natural gas). Inhalation is the most common route of exposure. CO binds to haemoglobin with a much higher affinity than oxygen to form carboxyhaemoglobin, preventing oxygen transport and resulting in tissue hypoxia. CO also combines with other haem compounds such as myoglobin and cytochrome oxidase. Treatment depends on severity, but for every patient with suspected CO poisoning, high flow (10-15L/min) of normobaric oxygen via non-rebreathing mask should be started immediately. Intubation may be required in more severe cases. Importantly, oxygen saturation by pulse oximetry should not be used to guide oxygen therapy because pulse oximeters cannot differentiate between CO-bound and O2-bound haemoglobin. Options A, B, and C do not provide adequate high-flow oxygen. Option E (hyperbaric oxygen) is indicated for severely poisoned patients who are comatose, have seizures or other neurologic abnormalities, or have myocardial ischaemia, but must be started and maintained on high-flow normobaric oxygen while arrangements are made.`,
