    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `John is 15 years old with a deep bite wound (considered dirty). He has completed his primary course of tetanus vaccination (5 doses total) with the last booster at age 4 years, which means it has been 11 years since his last booster. For dirty wounds in a patient with complete vaccination, the decision relies on the time elapsed since the last booster dose. Since more than 5 years have elapsed since his last booster dose, he needs another immediate booster dose with a tetanus-containing vaccine. For a 15-year-old (age 10-18 years), the preferred formulation is dTpa (diphtheria, tetanus, and acellular pertussis for ages 10-18 years). However, dT (adult diphtheria and tetanus toxoids without pertussis) is also an acceptable option for older individuals. Option A (DTPa) is a child formulation used up to the 10th birthday and is not appropriate for a 15-year-old. Option B (TT alone) is not currently available in Australia. Option D (TT plus TIG) is only indicated for persons with no, incomplete, or uncertain tetanus vaccination history. Option E (DTPw) is an older whole-cell pertussis formulation no longer used. The best answer is dT, which is appropriate for his age and vaccination status.`,
