    id: "em-amedex-0026",
    topic: "Emergency Medicine",
    subtopic: "Insect sting allergic reaction management",
    stem: `A 52-year-old farmer, who had been stung by bees several times before, comes to you for advice because the last time he was stung at the back of his hand a few days ago, he developed a large itchy swelling at the sting site which was different from previous times. The swelling went down in 2-3 days with no complications or remaining symptoms. Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice for him?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `He needs to take steroids after he is stung.` },
      { label: "B", text: `He needs to take NSAIDs after he is stung.` },
      { label: "C", text: `He should carry an EpiPen with him and use it immediately after he is stung.` },
      { label: "D", text: `He needs to take antihistamine tablets regularly.` },
      { label: "E", text: `He needs to apply antihistamine cream on the sting site immediately.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `As described by the Australian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA), there are three degrees of allergic reactions to stinging insects which are as follows: 1. An isolated local reaction refers to a rash or swelling without other symptoms. These individuals have a 10% risk of developing anaphylaxis with the next sting. 2. A generalized reaction with no life-threatening signs refers to the development of hives and discomfort without respiratory symptoms or hypotension. It is more common in children and predisposes an individual to a 1 in 10 chance of progression to anaphylaxis. 3. Anaphylaxis is a severe and potentially fatal allergic reaction with symptoms such as respiratory symptoms, vomiting, abdominal pain, and hypotension. Adults are at higher risk of developing anaphylaxis than children. It claims the lives of about 3 Australians each year. The scenario represents a patient whose presentation is consistent with the first group (isolated reaction only). According to current guidelines, taking NSAIDs for decreasing the symptoms such as pain and swelling is the most appropriate option. Although patients with localized reactions to stings are at a 10% risk of developing anaphylaxis in the next incident, the fact that he has been frequently stung and had only local reactions makes anaphylaxis an even less likely outcome for him. Therefore, EpiPen (option C) would be unnecessary. A prescription for EpiPen, after adequate education on anaphylaxis and the use of autoinjectors, is indicated in the following patients: Personal history of anaphylaxis and continuing risk from allergen exposure; or if the triggers for anaphylaxis were unidentified. Food allergies in a patient with persistent moderate to severe asthma. Systemic mastocytosis or mast cell disorders in a patient with a previous generalized allergy to insect stings or on venom immunotherapy. A short course (1-3 days) of oral antihistamines (e.g., diphenhydramine) may be indicated for a more generalized reaction without life-threatening signs of anaphylaxis, or if the swelling and itch persists. This patient has none of the indications for antihistamines (option D). Even if he did, taking antihistamine tablets regularly would not be advised. While topical steroids may be effective in alleviating the localized symptoms of insect stings, there is no evidence supporting the added benefits of systemic steroids and prescribing oral steroids (option A) would be incorrect. Unlike topical steroids, topical antihistamines (option E) are unlikely to relieve a localized reaction and are not recommended.`,
