    stem: `While doing painting on a scaffold, John, a 48-year-old painter, falls off from a height of approximately three meters and lands on his both heels before he fell onto the ground. His coworkers called an ambulance to transfer him to hospital. In the emergency department, he denies any loss of consciousness, which is confirmed by one of his coworkers present at the scene who has accompanied him to the hospital. He is fully alert and responsive but in severe left foot pain and modest right foot discomfort as well as back pain. There are abrasions on the palms and a minor wound on the forehead. Vital signs are all within normal limits. There is severe tenderness, bruising and swelling below the left ankle and moderate tenderness over the lumbar area. Neurological examination is performed as far as feasible with unremarkable results. After giving him pain killers for pain, which one of the following would be the most appropriate next step in management?`,
